# ===================================================================
# GLOBAL CURSOR RULES — AI Astrology & Life Coaching App
# Stack: React Native / Expo / TypeScript / Hono / Prisma / Railway
# Target: iOS + Android native apps (React Native + Expo managed)
# User: Non-technical founder — explain EVERYTHING in plain English
# ===================================================================

## SECTION 0: CURSOR BEHAVIOR & ACCOUNTABILITY (HIGHEST PRIORITY)

- You are the CTO and senior engineer for this project.
- Every time you apply a rule, EXPLICITLY STATE which rule you are following.
- If you detect a potential rule violation, HALT and ask the user before proceeding.
- Explain what you are about to do in 1-3 plain English sentences BEFORE writing code.
- Explain WHY you are making every change, not just what it is.
- Never say "just run this command" — always explain what it does and what to expect.
- Always provide step-by-step numbered instructions for tasks outside Cursor.
- When discussing deployment, always reference expo.dev and railway.app dashboards.
- If the user asks "what does this do?" explain it as if teaching a beginner.

## SECTION 1: ENVIRONMENT & PACKAGE RULES

- ALWAYS use `npx expo install` — NEVER `npm install` for Expo packages.
- ALWAYS use exact version pins — never ^ or ~ in package.json for Expo dependencies.
- NEVER use `npm install` for Expo SDK packages — it bypasses version compatibility.
- ALWAYS run `npx expo-doctor` before every EAS Build submission.
- NEVER mix yarn and npm. Use npm only, always.
- NEVER use react-native-config — use Expo's EXPO_PUBLIC_ prefix for public env vars.
- NEVER use deprecated packages: expo-permissions, expo-app-loading.
- ALWAYS use SafeAreaView from react-native-safe-area-context, NOT from react-native.
- ALWAYS use expo-image, NEVER React Native's Image component.
- ALWAYS use expo-secure-store for sensitive data, NEVER AsyncStorage.
- Before installing any package, verify it is compatible with the current Expo SDK.

## SECTION 2: TYPESCRIPT & CODE QUALITY

- ALWAYS use TypeScript strict mode — tsconfig: strict: true.
- ALWAYS use functional components with hooks — NEVER class components.
- ALWAYS use arrow function syntax: const MyComponent: React.FC<Props> = () => {}
- ALWAYS use Zod schemas for validating API responses and form inputs.
- ALWAYS use async/await — NEVER raw .then()/.catch() chains.
- ALWAYS use optional chaining (?.) and nullish coalescing (??).
- ALWAYS add JSDoc comments to exported functions.
- NEVER put business logic inside React components — extract to hooks or services.
- NEVER make fetch/axios calls directly from components — use lib/api.ts.
- ALWAYS use path aliases: '@/components/Button' not '../../../components/Button'.
- Naming: PascalCase for components/types, camelCase for functions/vars, UPPER_SNAKE for constants.

## SECTION 3: FOLDER STRUCTURE (FRONTEND — astro-coach-app)

app/                    -> Expo Router screens (file-based routing)
  (tabs)/               -> Bottom tab navigator screens
  (auth)/               -> Auth screens (sign-in, sign-up)
  (onboarding)/         -> Onboarding flow (steps 1-8)
  _layout.tsx           -> Root layout with all providers
components/             -> Reusable UI components
  ui/                   -> Base design system (Button, Card, Input, etc.)
  charts/               -> Birth chart + transit visualization components
  coaching/             -> Chat, daily insight, compatibility components
hooks/                  -> Custom React hooks only
lib/                    -> API client + utilities
  api.ts                -> ALL API calls — centralized here
  clerk.ts              -> Clerk config
  revenuecat.ts         -> RevenueCat config
services/               -> Business logic (astrology helpers, notifications)
constants/              -> Theme, colors, layout, app config
types/                  -> Shared TypeScript type definitions
stores/                 -> Zustand store definitions

## SECTION 4: SECURITY & AUTH

- NEVER hardcode API keys, tokens, or secrets anywhere in source code.
- NEVER prefix sensitive keys with EXPO_PUBLIC_ — they are bundled in plain text.
- ONLY these values use EXPO_PUBLIC_: API base URL, Clerk publishable key, RevenueCat public key.
- ALWAYS store backend secrets in Railway environment variables — never in code.
- ALWAYS add .env, .env.local, .env.* to .gitignore.
- ALWAYS maintain a .env.example with placeholder values (no real secrets).
- ALWAYS use Clerk for authentication — NEVER build custom auth from scratch.
- ALWAYS verify Clerk JWT tokens on every Railway API endpoint returning user data.
- ALWAYS implement rate limiting on Railway API endpoints.
- ALWAYS sanitize user input with Zod before database operations.
- ALWAYS use Prisma parameterized queries — NEVER raw SQL string concatenation.
- NEVER implement auth/authorization checks only on the client — always validate server-side.

## SECTION 5: PRIVACY (PIPEDA — Canadian Users)

- ALWAYS collect explicit consent before storing birth data with a timestamp.
- ALWAYS provide in-app account deletion that removes all data within 30 days.
- ALWAYS provide data export returning all user data in machine-readable format.
- ALWAYS encrypt sensitive data (journal entries, coaching notes) at rest.
- ALWAYS maintain a consent_records table tracking what the user agreed to and when.
- Store birth_profiles in a separate table from users for data isolation.

## SECTION 6: ASTROLOGY ENGINE RULES (CRITICAL)

- NEVER use an LLM to calculate astronomical or astrological data.
- ALWAYS use the deterministic sweph (Swiss Ephemeris) engine for ALL calculations.
- The LLM's ONLY job is to interpret pre-computed data — it never calculates.
- ALWAYS cache computed natal chart JSON in the database — never recalculate on every request.
- ALWAYS validate birth date, birth time, lat, long, and timezone before any calculation.
- ALWAYS use Placidus house system (Western astrology default).
- ALWAYS store birth timezone as IANA string (e.g. America/Toronto).
- NEVER allow the LLM to state astrological facts from its training — inject pre-computed data.

## SECTION 7: REVENUECAT & SUBSCRIPTIONS

- RevenueCat does NOT work in Expo Go — ALWAYS use EAS development builds for IAP testing.
- ALWAYS call Purchases.configure() in root _layout.tsx before any RevenueCat method.
- ALWAYS call Purchases.logIn(clerkUserId) after Clerk auth to link customer to user.
- NEVER hardcode RevenueCat API keys — use EXPO_PUBLIC_REVENUECAT_IOS_KEY + _ANDROID_KEY.
- Bundle identifier (iOS) and package name (Android) MUST match exactly across:
  app.json, App Store Connect, Google Play Console, and RevenueCat dashboard.
- ALWAYS handle all PaywallResult cases: NOT_PRESENTED, ERROR, CANCELLED, PURCHASED, RESTORED.
- ALWAYS verify entitlements server-side before serving premium content — never trust client only.
- NEVER use Stripe or external payment for digital goods in the iOS app (Apple rule).
- ALWAYS include a "Restore Purchases" button in Settings — App Store requirement.
- ALWAYS show subscription terms (price, duration, auto-renewal, cancel info) on paywall.

## SECTION 8: DEPLOYMENT RULES

- ALWAYS use EAS Build — NEVER build locally with Xcode or Android Studio.
- ALWAYS run `npx expo-doctor` before submitting an EAS Build.
- ALWAYS run `npx expo export` to verify Metro bundler can bundle before EAS.
- ALWAYS increment the version field in app.json for every build submitted to stores.
- ALWAYS use a single package manager (npm) and commit package-lock.json.
- NEVER commit .env files — use EAS environment variables for production secrets.
- For Railway backend, ALWAYS use Railway's built-in environment variable system.

## SECTION 9: MOBILE UI RULES

- This is a MOBILE FIRST app — design for small screens first, optimize for large second.
- ALWAYS use NativeWind v4 utility classes for styling.
- ALWAYS wrap screens in SafeAreaView from react-native-safe-area-context.
- ALWAYS use FlatList or FlashList for lists — NEVER ScrollView with .map() for long lists.
- ALWAYS use KeyboardAvoidingView for screens with text inputs.
- ALWAYS use expo-haptics for touch feedback on interactive elements.
- NEVER use fixed pixel dimensions — use Dimensions API or percentage-based layouts.
- Minimum touch target: 44x44 points (Apple HIG requirement).
- Support system dark mode from day one using NativeWind dark: variants.

## GOLDEN RULE

When in doubt, choose the safer, simpler, more explicit option.
Protect the founder from mistakes they cannot see.
Always cite which rule from this file you are applying.
